# Finance Dashboard Backend

A role-based finance management backend built with Spring Boot. The system allows users to manage financial records, view dashboard 
analytics, and enforces strict access control based on user roles.

## Tech Stack

- Java 17
- Spring Boot
- Spring Security
- JSON Web Tokens (JWT)
- MySQL
- Spring Data JPA / Hibernate
- Maven

### Features

- JWT based authentication and authorization
- Role based access control (VIEWER, ANALYST, ADMIN)
- Financial records management with filtering
- Dashboard summary APIs for analytics
- Input validation and global error handling

#### Project Overview:-
I have created Finance Data Processing and Access Control Backend system using Java, Spring boot and MySQL as databse. You can perform 
CRUD operations on Records and User data if you have rights to do so. So when you will start the application, the spring boot perform 
its tasks like bean creation, spring security (securing endpoints) and many more. I have tested all the APIs using Postman and used 
Eclipse IDE for creating project. There is three main part of this project. First is the main method from where application starts. 
Second is the Record and Dashboard handling part where you will find the different java files to manage record and dashboard summary. 
Third and the most interesting part is the security part which handles the authentication and authorization using spring security 
and JWT.

At first you will register yourself by hitting the "POST: api/auth/register" API and providing username, password role in JSON body.
Now your username and hashed password is stored in database with role.
Now you will hit login api "POST: api/auth/login" and passing username and password in the body of Postman. The security part of the 
application will check if the username exist in database. If the user exists, now your sent password is hashed again and compared with
the stored hash password. If it matches, a JWT token is generated which contains your username and role. Now with every request you 
send that token in the header tab, and application checks your role, and if your role permits you to hit that API, you will get the 
result otherwise 403 error will be thrown. There are three types of User:- VIEWER,ANALYST,ADMIN. An user with VIEWER role is only 
allowed to see the data. User with ANALYST role can access differnt Dashboard summary APIs which is useful for an analyst. And User 
with ADMIN right can perform any action in the application. 

I have used clean architecture and followed Controller, Service and Repository layer design.


I have used JWT for authentication and authorization because it is stateless in nature and since role is also mentioned in the token 
so application doesn't need to look database for on every request.

Before running this project, edit the application.properties file with real values.
